<p>In <i><b>Hustler Magazine, Inc. v. Falwell</b></i>, <a href="/wiki/Case_citation" title="Case citation">485 U.S. 46</a> (1988), the <a href="/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States" title="Supreme Court of the United States">United States Supreme Court</a> held, in a unanimous 8-0 decision (Justice Kennedy took no part in the consideration or decision of the case), that the <a href="/wiki/First_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution" title="First Amendment to the United States Constitution">First Amendment's</a> free-speech guarantee prohibits awarding damages to <a href="/wiki/Public_figure" title="Public figure">public figures</a> to compensate for emotional distress intentionally inflicted upon them.</p>
<p>Thus, <i>Hustler</i> magazine's parody of <a href="/wiki/Jerry_Falwell" title="Jerry Falwell">Jerry Falwell</a> was deemed to be within the law, leading to a reversal of the jury verdict in favor of Falwell, who had previously been awarded $150,000 in damages by a lower court.</p>
